2961-960-0009	The dialogue is primarily concerned with the animal creation, including under this term the heavenly bodies, and with man only as one among the animals.
2961-960-0010	But he has not as yet defined this intermediate territory which lies somewhere between medicine and mathematics, and he would have felt that there was as great an impiety in ranking theories of physics first in the order of knowledge as in placing the body before the soul.
2961-960-0011	With Heraclitus, he acknowledges the perpetual flux. Like Anaxagoras, he asserts the predominance of mind, although admitting an element of necessity which reason is incapable of subduing. Like the Pythagoreans, he supposes the mystery of the world to be contained in number.
